content: Pros:  - Relatively simple to use user interface (compared to similar camera apps) - ability to save dag files for later editing (like a raw file). Cons: The jpeg version of the photos taken look rubbish! You need to edit all the dag files in another program and export them to make the pictures look good. I compared this apps jpeg to the ones taken on Samsung default camera app and Google camera app. Googles and Samsung came pretty close and you could see most of the details. With this app the details are jumbled into a blur at any contrast in the picture. This makes it impossible to use for quick shots on auto (unless you want to take the time to edit and export a picture from the dag file).  I won't ask for a refund since I hope this will be fixed, but it's a thing that should be mentioned in the description of the app for people who want to take ok photos with saved dag files as a bonous.

just bought it.  here's my initial 1-minute-experience-review:  i'm a professional photographer, and i really like it :D  Obviously can't replace our 5D3s, but it's great for a for a snappy phone camera app. I have an old Google Nexus5 (which is famous for having a terrible camera), and this app has really improved the camera.  PROS:  super fast shutter. full control of all exposure variables (shutter speed, ISO, but not aperture). manual (lockable) focus control. apparently shoots in raw (.DNG), but i haven't played with these.  CONS: no manual aperture control!  I would have bought this a long time ago, at full price, if i knew the app existed. Now I regret just ordering the Panasonic DMC-CM1 :( Well at least it'll give me full manual aperture control :')

I love the manual control of focus distance, shutter speed and RAW support. However, there are a few issues:  1) It can't replace the default app because it doesn't have the front-facing camera and video. 2) It's full-screen, good, but to get the Android navigation, you swipe up, which almost always accidentally takes a picture. 3) The volume-rocker shooting doesn't work most of the time (in the Android default app, it always works). Needing to touch the screen is exceptionally annoying. 4) The preview image looks significantly different than the final image when you change settings. For example, taking a picture at ISO 100 with a shutter speed of 0.8s in my office produces an overexposed image (of course), but the preview image is quite dark.  I'm not giving up on it, but it can't be my "daily driver" camera app yet.

I really like the idea of a manual camera application.  This app provides access to all of the controls I expect.  The pictures and control are top-notch but the UX could use some changes. Exiting the application is non-intuitive.  Just about every single Android application has a single button to exit the application.  It took me a few tries to remember to swipe from the right to get the  buttons (even though it's mentioned in the tutorial) it's just not like other applications which means it doesn;'t have the same android feel. The other oddity is the switch to view pictures.  You can click on the thumbnail view of the photos, much like other camera apps. Oddly when you view the pictures, the 3 button controls for normal apps show up.  If you exit the program from the photos when you launch it, it resumes viewing the photos.  I would have expected it to go directly to the camera controls; I want my camera app to always be ready to take a shot. The last bit on adjusting the manual controls.  I really like the big wheel on the right to adjust the value for the feature (like shutter speed or ISO).  What I don't like is the long press to reset, would prefer a toggle on the big wheel.

This app is worthy of praise based on its interface alone.  Clean, no-nonsense, and very functional, while aesthetically pleasing.  I love the tap-to-lock, spin-to-change, hold-to-automate paradigm.  It's very intuitive.  Focus is fast and mostly accurate, and the app has very little shutter lag.  The dev changed the settings to be saved session to session, so the only bug or oddity that I've noticed is that setting infinity focus on my Nexus 5 results in a very slightly OOF image.  True, there are some missing features here, but I'd rather have the developer implement more photographic features than try compete with things that Google already has locked down.  After all, my DSLR doesn't do HDR+/photosphere/panoramas/digital zoom/etc, and I've never missed them while shooting with it.  Which brings me to a few feature requests.  Useful things that I'd like to see include an intervalometer, auto-iso (in manual shutter mode), exposure bracketing, burst shooting, and a live histogram.

This app opens up a new realm of possibilities for Android camera phone users with devices that support it. If you know what you're doing, the photos come out a lot better.  However, the auto-mode I feel is no better than the stock Lollipop camera on my Nexus 5. It's not going to turn the Nexus 5 into a point-and-shoot monster. Like the stock camera app, it selects too high of an ISO, resulting in grainy images; most noticeable in low light. This is where the manual controls are really useful, as it lets you turn down the ISO while the at same time turning down the shutter speed if need be for low light situations. I would really like some preset auto modes; especially one that has a lower ISO bias at the expense of shutter speed which is a setting that would be really good for still life photos. Only bug I found is that at low light situations in manual mode when im fiddling around with the ISO or shutter settings, it sometimes doesn't want to take a picture when i click on the button. I'm not exactly sure why. It's usually in very dark scenarios though. And also, it doesn't want to seem to stay in manual mode when i go back into the app after exiting.

Need access to system buttons on nexus 5.  Can't exit app with out viewing photo and using home button. Also needs pinch to zoom.  Otherwise I'm keeping it and you may keep my $2.  Well worth it...
Like stock but not super slow and the pictures seem just as good.

The stock Nexus 5 camera app is horrible - difficult to focus, and terrible at exposure and white balance. This app changes all that, with fine tuned settings I didn't even think possible. Only thing I'd like to see added is custom profiles for settings.
I did not realize the nexus 5 camera allowed this much control over the basis settings.
Tried it on nexus 5. Have no regrets way better than any other manual camera app out there. Unfortunately doesn't have a portrait mode.
One of the best cameras I've used. Great use of screen space w/ settings on either side of 4:3 viewfinder. Only thing missing is burst.
Works perfectly on Nexus 5

Manual controls work great, design is clean but the app is lacking quite a few features like HDR, zoom, front camera support, etc.

The layout is simple and fluid to use with two thumbs, really glad I found this. An improvement I would like to see is the ability to save my settings for the next time the app opens, at least setting for the shutter sound
Ugly icon, please get a designer to do a great icon for this great app :)

Glad that someone is taking advantage of the new camera API in Lollipop. Hoping video is on the development roadmap. Would love to see more advanced video features than Google currently offers on their camera app.

content: I have only played with the app a little at this point but I love having all manual controls. The one thing I would like to see added would be aperature/shutter priority modes
This app is great on my Nexus 6 and shoot pictures really fast, but how can you not have a zoom function?
First time I see an app capable of replacing google camera and the most important: it is far better at any aspect. Better interface (love the design) and huge variety in settings.
Shoots fast and has support for RAW.  Reminds me of my DSLR!  Wish it had video, so it'd be great to hear from the DEV about possibility of adding it later.

The camera seems pretty fast on my Nexus 6. But it doesn't seem to be able to toggle to the front facing camera, and I'd like the option of taking photos as a 16:9 image. Am I missing any settings where I can enable these options?
It'd be awesome if you could set it as the camera that opens when you swipe from the lock screen!
Nexus 5 blazing fast shutter... Wow! üôå

Desperately needs the ability to save camera settings on closure. Major flaw at the moment that I am sure will eventually be fixed or provided the option soon (or at least I hope). Will be a 5 star app after that.
Can I shoot video with this?

Everything seems excellent especially the RAW capability. The main virtue of this app is definitely the clarity of the design. Three things though -  from what I can tell there's no optical zoom control. Also, whenever I start the app up it forgets the settings I'd previously programmed in. Lastly, it's not yet possible to use the app as a default camera from the app screen. Hopefully these will come in a future update...nothing fancy with the zoom - just a simple bar at the bottom to zoom in and out with.

I had 0 expectations other than a reasonably nice options layout around the canvas. After a couple shots I was pretty happy about the quality and the fast focus time.The whole range of options that are easily accessible is also a plus.  Good job, I hope you keep working on this

I purchased this app for my Xperia Z with Lollipop and it crashes everytime I start it. I paid Rs. 174 for this application instead of Rs. 124 and it is a complete waste of money. Please do not purchase this app! Please refund my money!
replyContent: Hi Deepak. Please don't blame us. This app requires device's hardware to be capable of manual settings. So far only Nexus 5 & 6 are. You shouldn't be even able to install the app on Xperia Z... I'm guessing you're using some custom ROM which bypassed this restriction...

content: Works really well on my nexus 5, snaps much quicker than the stock camera and the full manual controls are really accessible and great to have. Well done. My only significant requests for right now; auto bracketing, and having the option of shutter or aperture priority modes would both be grand.
Easy and fast great experience
replyContent: So why only 4 stars? ;)

content: Very nice app.  Few bugs, I will update my review when they are resolved.  Sound setting is not saved and defaults to on everytime I open the app.
Hands down the BEST Android camera. Finally a camera comparable to the iPhone cameras. The interface and manual controls are perfect. The only complaint is that the settings don't stick upon restart.

The UI of the built-in Nexus 6 camera app is awful so this is such a pleasant surprise. Note, Camera FV-5 has similar manual control but the UI is no where near as nice as Manual Camera's. When you press the shutter, it is instantaneous, which again is a huge improvement on the default camera app on Lollipop.  One of my favorite features is the max brightness setting.  Suggestions (in order of easiest to hardest): 1. Mention the use of the new Android Camera API in your description. Mention that it's only for Nexus devices for now. Maybe keep a short list of devices that it's known to work well with. 2. Bracket mode so we can do post processing HDR 3. Built-in HDR
Great control!
So far everything is good. Hope to see the "save settings" update in the near future.
Had issues with focus and right manual focus would allow me to control it but the dial had no impact on the image at all.
It's still early days for me but so far it's great! The feature I think that's missing right now is the ability to choose where to save the DNG files to.

content: Love it on N5. Being able to set marco/close focus and moving in is one great example if why this is useful.

content: This app not only looks amazing but it takes ridiculously good quality photos
Takes advantage of the new API's, great ui, great pictures.  Can't wait to see what the dev does with this app, glad to support.
A few bugs still. Flash still fires even when it's set to "off".

I love the camera layout. Takes nice quality photos on manual or auto. Looking to try out some more. I've always wanted to be able to adjust my photos when I don't have my regular camera with me. Ugly icon though.
I was looking for a camera with manual focus to get cleat and crisp pictures. This app does it and it's awesome.  Only thing that I wish it had was zoom.

I cant believe what this app can. Its awesome. My nexus 5 is like a new phone now. I love the interface! Hands down the best camera app for the nexus 5 with all (and by all i mean REALLY all) manual settings. Thanks and keep up your great work.

Lovely app. I just have a few suggestions. Support for portrait, swing the interface around and rotate the image data. HDR, I use it a lot with the default camera app. Volume button shutter control. Remember my mute volume setting. The icon is almost invisible on a black background, such as the app drawer. Great work though!
Just downloaded and tried half a dozen app for my Nexus 6 and this is by far the best in my low light tests.

I'm looking camera app that can manually setting like Nokia app, and I'm encouraging my self to buy this app. So here's my review 1. The result of the pictures need to be improve. It looks like the pictures taken by this app is to much compressing. I'm serious. 2. Your app is asking for location permission. I can't find anywhere inside the app to turn off the Geo tag. You must respect buyers privacy so we can trust the developer. 3. My phone easily get hot when using this app.
replyContent: Hi Lucky :) JPEG compression issue is now fixed. Could you please contact us (email is in the app) and give us some more details regarding those other issues?

content: I was hoping someone would write a camera with the Android 5.0 API and they did :)  It shows this is version 1.0: e.g. still uses flash sometimes (due to AF? even when off), seems to forget sound off setting, crashes if you leave it open and lock the phone. Hopefully that can be improved; stuff like RAW would be cool too.
replyContent: Hi David :) All the issues you've listed are fixed in version 1.1. And RAW support is on our "todo" list for future releases ;) Thanks!
